fields: Anatomy is the branch of biology concerned with the study of the {{c1::structure of organisms}} and their parts.

Two types of approaches for gross anatomy:

1) {{c1::Systemic::studying organ systems}}
2) {{c1::Regional::studying the body region by region}}

Two types of "clinical" approaches to examining body content:

1) {{c1::Surface Anatomy::examining surface features of the body to try to determine location and condition of deeper structures}}
2) {{c1::Imaging Anatomy::the use of x-ray, ultrasound, magnetic resonance imaging and computed tomography to examine internal structures non-invasively}}

{{c1::Histology::type of study}}

•the study of cells and tissues of the body
•structures only visible with light or electron microscopy
•histochemistry and immunocytochemistry often used to demonstrate specific components of cells or tissues

{{c1::Neuroanatomy::type of anatomy}}

The study of the central nervous system: brain & spinal cord

{{c1::Developmental Anatomy (Embryology)::type of anatomy}}

•includes gametogenesis, fertilization, and developing of the embryo and fetus as well as support tissues (placenta, amnion, chorion)
•is foundational to understanding the gross anatomy of the body
•includes the study of congenital defects
"Volar" is another term used to refer the {{c1::palm}}.
